exception handling

eloquent, ch.8

(1) raising an exception
    - jumps out of the current function and its callers
    - all the way down to the first call that started the current execution
(2) catching an exception
    -  allows to address the problem and then continue to run the program

EXAMPLE
function comp(input) {
    if (typeof input === "number") return input + 1;
    throw new Error(input + " is NaN."); // (1)
}

function input(val) {
    return comp(val);
}

try { // (2)
    console.log(input(3));  // 4
    console.log(input("3"));// Something went wrong: 3 is NaN.
} catch (error) {
    console.log("Something went wrong: " + error.message);
}
